The earrings have a polished shiny finish and are made from 925 sterling silver with cubic zirconia detailing. This item was made from recycled sterling silver. These earrings can be paired with ear cuffs for an on-trend stacked look This is the perfect touch of sparkle to dress up any outfit!

fields.description: Cubic Zirconia hoop earrings that are 15mm in diameter and 2mm in thickness with a polished shiny finish. The earrings are made from 925 sterling silver with rose gold plated finish and cubic zirconia detailing. This item was made from recycled sterling silver.

fields.name: Temple Bar Yellow Gold Earrings
fields.description: These earrings are 925 sterling silver and are finished with 18ct gold plating. They are approximately 5mm in length and 1mm in thickness. They have a polished shiny finish with cubic zirconia stones that sparkle endlessly. This item was made from recycled sterling silver. Look to these earrings as your everyday ear stack companions.

fields.description: Silver cubic zirconia stud earrings made from 925 sterling silver. They are approximately 6mm in size and have a polished shiny finish with cubic zirconia stone. These earrings add shimmer and sparkle to any look and are a classic eye-catcher!

fields.description: Spike hoop earrings with cubic zirconia detailing that will shine continuously! They have a 10mm drop from top of spike to bottom and a hoop size with approximately 15mm diameter and 1.5mm hoop thickness. Spikes are removable and hoops may be worn separately if you choose. This item was made from 925 recycled sterling silver and is finished with 18ct rose gold plating. Ideal for special occasions and a perfect gift for a loved one!

fields.description: Rectangle Hoop Earrings with 12mm hoop and 1mm hoop thickness. This item was made from recycled 925 sterling silver with 18ct yellow gold plating. Perfect to add a bit of edge to any outfit!

fields.description: Engravable yellow gold plated bar necklace with cubic zirconia white stone. Approx 25mm in size and 1.5mm in thickness and can be extended 42/45cm. This item was made from 925 recycled sterling silver and is finished with 18ct gold plating.

fields.description: Horseshoe pendant with a polished shiny finish. The chain is approximately 8 mm in size and can be extended 38/41cm. This item was made from recycled sterling silver.

This diamond product has a Lifetime Guarantee and is sustainable and environmentally friendly. The perfect showstopper gift to turn heads.

fields.description: Zig zag bar sterling silver pendant with rose gold plating. The length is approximately 25mm left to right and 5mm top to bottom and can be extended 42/45cm. This item is 925 sterling silver and is finished with 18ct gold plating.

fields.description: Rhodium-plated dot chain bracelet with polished shiny finish. The chain can be extended 17/19cm. This item was made from recycled sterling silver.

fields.title: Diamonds Are Forever: Why You Should Buy Ethically-Sourced Jewellery
fields.body:
Treating ourselves to luxury goods, whether it’s an expensive fragrance, a designer handbag or a piece of jewellery, makes us feel good. But in this booming market, not many people consider the ethics behind their purchases. “It can’t be bad if it cost so much money,” is something people say to me time and time again.

I’m sorry to break the news to you, but that couldn’t be further from the truth. In the jewellery sector alone, ethical concerns are rife, from the methods used to mine gold and diamonds to the sometimes dubious production practices in the Far East. They are what made me turn my back on the traditional fine jewellery industry and concentrate my efforts on creating ethical jewellery.

What ethical jewellery boils down to is traceability. If the materials used in a piece of jewellery are traceable, the buyer can make an informed choice about its provenance. Not all countries have the same stringent regulations in place, so knowing the country of origin of a precious metal or gemstone is the first step towards making an informed decision about a jewel’s ethical credentials.

Sustainability is an important consideration too. I’m sure you, like me, want that piece of jewellery you are wearing to benefit, not damage the world. From people displacement and deforestation to soil contamination and dangerous working conditions, unsustainable practices are, sadly, commonplace in the mining industry. It is therefore important to know precisely where the materials a piece of jewellery is made from originate, right down to the exact mine. The same applies in relation to where and how a piece of jewellery was manufactured. Only then will you be able to determine whether a piece of jewellery has been produced sustainably.

In recent years, Fairtrade Gold and Fairmined Gold certification systems have developed fully. Both organisations have become stronger voices in the industry, and a growing number of small jewellers, like me, are choosing to use certified fair traded gold and silver in their jewellery (unfortunately, very little platinum comes from these schemes).

Also, we are seeing more and more fair trade jewels, manufactured by communities in need, where that commercial activity is all they have. Jewellery has the power to change lives, to bring wealth to those living in poverty, and that is a very powerful message that we can all be part of.

A good place to start with all this “green talk” is the 10 principles of fair trade, as prescribed by the World Fair Trade Organization (WFTO), which I adhere to as an ethical jeweller. If you want to know more, visit their fantastic website. 

For a jewel to be truly ethical, the designer will have considered all these factors, and many others besides, including how many hands the materials passed through and where it was made. A commonly used phrase when talking about ethical jewellery is “from mine to market”. This means that the journey of a piece of ethical jewellery should be direct and traceable, from the mine all the way to the customer.

A favourite piece of jewellery will be loved, treasured and worn time and time again, but to truly feel good about it, it has to be beautiful inside and out. Buying a piece of ethical jewellery shows that you know better. It shows that you care about the environment. On a more personal scale, it shows that you care about the people who played a part in its creation, right down to the miners – and their families – who were responsible for extracting the gold from the Earth. Ultimately, it shows that you want to make a difference with your choices, and that is a very powerful message.

Put simply, like you, I want to change the world. That is a very bold statement, I know! But I am deeply committed to it. With pressure growing from both the inside - designer like me, and outside - customers like you, the world of retail is changing. Consumers are asking questions about where their jewellery came from and designers are choosing to care. I care for the piece of jewellery that you are going to wear on your finger, which is why I can tell you precisely where the gold came from. In fact, I have visited the exact mine and watched the miners at work. I did this because I am proud of the jewellery I create and I want you to feel proud of it too – and to spread the word to everyone around you.

Share your style from your Maisigh order to be in with a chance of winning a discount on your next order!
